rdshire, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Weston, Staffordshire, England":"Weston, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Leaver","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Lever  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lever","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname for a fleet-footed or timid person, from Old French <i>levre</i> ‘hare’ (from Latin <i>lepus</i>, genitive <i>leporis</i>). It may also have been a metonymic occupational name for a hunter of hares.","English: topographic name for someone who lived in a place thickly grown with rushes, from Old English <i>lǣfer</i> ‘rush, reed, iris’. Compare   Laver  . Great and Little Lever in Greater Manchester are named with this word (in a collective sense), so the surname may also be a habitational name from these places.","Dutch and North German: from the medieval personal names <i>Lever</i>, a variant of <i>Liever</i> (see   Lieber  ), and <i>Levert</i>, a variant of <i>Lievert</i> (see   Liebhart  ). This surname is very rare in Germany."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":8,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705184,"age":18,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705185,"age":28,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Leaver was born in 1078, in Weston, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Adam de Leaver II, was 28 and her mother, Johanna Garnett, was 28. She married Ralph de Weston in 1104, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1130, in her hometown, at the age of 52, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1078–1130":"1078–1130","1074–Male":"1074–Surnud","1073–1126":"1073–1126","1090–1180":"1090–1180","1113–1166":"1113–1166","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1090":"1090","after 1090":"pärast 1090","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","1050":"1050","1180":"1180","1106":"1106","1104":"1104","1126":"1126","1113":"1113","1078":"1078","1166":"1166","Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England":"Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Weston, Staffordshire, England":"Weston, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1078–1130":"1078–1130","1074–Male":"1074–Kuollut","1073–1126":"1073–1126","1090–1180":"1090–1180","1113–1166":"1113–1166","1050–Male":"1050–Kuollut","1050–Female":"1050–Kuollut","1090":"1090","after 1090":"1090 jälkeen","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","1050":"1050","1180":"1180","1106":"1106","1104":"1104","1126":"1126","1113":"1113","1078":"1078","1166":"1166","Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England":"Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Weston, Staffordshire, England":"Weston, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1078–1130":"1078–1130","1074–Male":"1074–Décédé","1073–1126":"10